    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">
On Thu, 6 Oct 1994, Robert L. Frost wrote, in response to Eglash&apos;s:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="28" relname="span">

 Its
&amp;gt; &amp;gt;          unconvincing to add on &quot;Oh, and our new democratic science
&amp;gt; &amp;gt;          will also avoid all the old pitfalls of socialist tyranny.&quot;
&amp;gt; &amp;gt;
&amp;gt; &amp;gt;          Why can&apos;t we use these issues as an offensive platform
&amp;gt; &amp;gt;          rather than dancing around them?
&amp;gt; 
&amp;gt; Fine idea. Suggestions? </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="29" relname="span">

Discussion on democracy and science has floated through talk about how to
respond to the backlash.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="30" relname="span">  I wonder how many people on this list are
familiar with some of the Nordic attempts to promote substantive
democratic discourse over technoscience issues? </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="18" relname="span"> Although I have had no
direct experience,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="22" relname="span"> the Danish consensus conferences look like the most
interesting innovation.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="span">  These involve assembling a group of lay people
in a specific local area to discuss their concerns regarding a particular
technoscience initiative (e.g., bio-technology), and using staff to help
them formulate a set of questions.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration">  These are referred to a panel of
experts for answers. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="20" relname="sequence"> The &quot;Consensus conference&quot; itself involves
assembling both groups to meet over a couple days in a community venue,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="20" relname="sequence">
and then the lay people write up a report of their conclusions.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="20" relname="elaboration">  Several
of these are organized in different places on the same issue, all
accompanied by media coverage and publicity. </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="concession"> 

The Danes I have met claim that while the Danish are generally the most
skeptical of the Fenno-Scandians about technology,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="23" relname="span"> Denmark has been able
to move forward more quickly on specific technological initiatives than
other Nordic countries.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="13" relname="volitional-cause">  These Danes also claim that the consensus
conference process has something to do with this result.  </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="26" relname="span">

In any case, the conferences offer one model of how to make technoscience
discourse more democratic.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="25" relname="span"> I&apos;m sure there are others.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="16" relname="elaboration"> (the Dutch have
something similar, the Norwegians trying to get them going.)</segment>
